  journal  = {Symposium (International) on Combustion},
  year     = {1985},
  volume   = {20},
  number   = {1},
  pages    = {857-870},
  abstract = {Similarities of the relative concentrations of the more stable polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) in very different combustion systems are striking. The formation of PAH and their secondary oxidation in flames of aliphatic and aromatic fuels is reported and discussed. Aromatics with side chains seem to play an important role for the formation of PAH both in the oxidation zone and in the burned gas. Remarkable similarities for the mass growth of soot and its time and temperature dependence have been found for a large number of fuels. Mass growth is interpreted in terms of soot surface reactions, mainly with acetylene. The reason for the decrease in surface reactivity is still not understood. Simultaneous oxidation of soot in the secondary oxidation zone, early recognized by Millikan,26 might explain the negative temperature dependence of the amount of soot formed. The formation of large ions occurs in a secondary ionization zone of sooting flames. There are striking differences in flames of aliphatic and aromatic fuel. The mechanism of ionization of large molecules and small soot particles still presents a problem. The role of charged particles in soot formation is discussed.},
}

