  abstract    = {Soot emission from fossil-fueled engines is a major environmental and health concern due to the carcinogenic nature of the soot precursors and the small soot particles that are not oxidized in the flame zone. Here, a new approach within the context of large-eddy simulation (LES) methodology is being developed in which a new multi-scale formulation will be used to capture the molecular processes that lead to molecular clustering, phase change and the subsequent soot formation and growth. This LES approach will be extended to include soot models based on the method of moments and the source terms in the soot model (that represent nucleation, growth and agglomeration) will be obtained using a combination of Molecular Dynamics and Monte Carlo simulation models. In the first six months of this research, a general simulation methodology to use multi-step kinetics with soot model has been developed and the accuracy of the reduced kinetics model in canonical flows determined. Integration of this reduced mechanism in a 2D/3D LES solver has also been accomplished.},
